  "In physics and mathematics, 'normal' means perpendicular (at a 90° angle). The normal force acts perpendicular to the surface. On a flat floor, it points straight up. On an inclined plane, it points away from the surface at a right angle.": "",
  "What does 'decompose' mean when referring to forces on an incline?": "",
  "To break a force into components along and perpendicular to the slope": "",
  "To remove forces from a diagram so fewer arrows are shown": "",
  "To combine all forces into one single resultant force vector": "",
  "To eliminate friction from the problem by making the surface smooth": "",
  "Decomposing a force means breaking it into two perpendicular components. On an inclined plane, we decompose the weight (mg) into a parallel component (mg sin θ along the slope) and a perpendicular component (mg cos θ into the surface).": "",
  "What does the term 'angle of repose' refer to?": "",
  "The maximum angle at which an object can stay on a slope without sliding": "",
  "The angle at which a thrown ball reaches its highest point in the air": "",
  "The angle between the normal force and the gravitational force vector": "",
  "The angle that gives the maximum distance for a projectile launched up": "",
  "The angle of repose is the steepest angle of an incline at which an object remains stationary without sliding. Beyond this angle, the component of gravity along the slope exceeds the maximum static friction, and the object slides. It is related to μₛ by tan θ = μₛ.": "",
  "What does 'perpendicular component' mean on an inclined plane?": "",
  "The part of the weight that presses into the surface of the incline": "",
  "The part of the weight that pulls the object down along the slope": "",
  "The friction force that acts along the surface of the inclined plane": "",
  "The applied force that pushes the object up the inclined plane": "",
  "The perpendicular component of weight on an incline is the part that pushes into the surface, equal to mg cos θ. This component is balanced by the normal force. It does not cause motion along the slope but determines how hard the object presses against the surface.": "",
  "What does 'parallel component' mean on an inclined plane?": "",
  "The part of the weight that acts along the slope and causes sliding": "",
  "The part of the weight that presses the object into the incline surface": "",
  "The normal force that the incline exerts on the object's bottom surface": "",
  "The applied force that a person exerts to push an object up the slope": "",
  "The parallel component of weight on an incline is mg sin θ. It acts along the slope, pulling the object downhill. This is the component responsible for causing the object to slide down the incline if friction is insufficient to hold it.": "",
