  "A student stacks books and tilts them to create a ramp. A block begins to slide when the angle reaches 25°. What does this tell the student about the coefficient of static friction?": "",
  "The coefficient of static friction equals sin 25° divided by cos 25° (tan 25°)": "",
  "The coefficient of static friction equals cos 25° divided by sin 25°": "",
  "The coefficient of static friction equals sin 25° times cos 25°": "",
  "The coefficient of static friction equals 25 divided by 90 degrees": "",
  "At the angle of repose, the object is about to slide, so maximum static friction equals the parallel component of gravity: μₛ mg cos θ = mg sin θ. Simplifying: μₛ = sin θ / cos θ = tan θ. So μₛ = tan 25° ≈ 0.47.": "",
  "In a lab, a student pushes a 6 kg box up a frictionless ramp tilted at 30° at constant speed. What applied force along the ramp is needed? (Use g = 10 m/s², sin 30° = 0.5)": "",
